# Expo Header Removal Pattern

## When to Remove Expo Headers

**Remove the default Expo header bar when:**
- Implementing a custom header with back button and title
- The page has its own navigation controls
- You want full control over the header appearance and behavior

## Implementation Steps

### 1. Update Layout Configuration

In `app/_layout.native.tsx`, add the page to Stack.Screen with `headerShown: false`:

```typescript
<Stack.Screen name="page-name" options={{ headerShown: false }} />
```

### 2. Add Custom Header with Top Padding

Implement a custom header with appropriate top padding to account for the status bar:

```typescript
{/* Header */}
<View style={{ 
  padding: 16, 
  paddingTop: Platform.OS === 'ios' ? 100 : 80, // Top padding for status bar
  borderBottomWidth: 1, 
  borderBottomColor: borderColor,
  backgroundColor: cardBackground,
  flexDirection: 'row',
  alignItems: 'center'
}}>
  <TouchableOpacity 
    style={{ marginRight: 16 }}
    onPress={() => router.back()}
  >
    <Ionicons name="arrow-back" size={24} color={textColor} />
  </TouchableOpacity>
  
  <ThemedText style={{ fontSize: 18, fontWeight: 'bold', color: textColor }}>
    Page Title
  </ThemedText>
</View>
```

## Padding Guidelines

**Platform-specific top padding:**
- **iOS**: 100px (accounts for status bar + safe area)
- **Android**: 80px (accounts for status bar)

**Adjust padding as needed:**
- Start with recommended values
- Increase if more breathing room is desired
- Test on both platforms to ensure proper positioning

## Examples in Codebase

- **Flashcards page**: Custom header with back button and "Flashcards: [Note Title]"
- **Other pages**: Follow the same pattern for consistency

## Benefits

- **Full control**: Customize header appearance and behavior
- **Consistent design**: Match app's design language
- **Better UX**: Integrate seamlessly with app navigation patterns
- **Platform optimization**: Proper spacing for iOS and Android

## Notes

- Only remove headers when implementing custom alternatives
- Ensure custom headers include proper back navigation
- Test on both iOS and Android to verify spacing
- Consider accessibility and touch target sizes
